ing how the always small aristocratic and gentry component dwindled andwas virtually extinct by the 1730s, the Presbyterians deriving their strength from the middling sorts - clergy, doctors, lawyers, merchants, traders and, in particular, successful farmers and those active in the rapidly growing linen trades - and among the laborious poor. It discusses how Presbyterians were part of the economically dynamic element of Irish society; how they took the lead in the emigration movement to the American colonies; and how they maintained links with Scotland and related to other communities, in Ireland and elsewhere. Later in the eighteenth century, the Presbyterian community went on to form the backbone of the Republican, separatist movement. ROBERT WHAN obtained his Ph.D. in History from Queen's University, Belfast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPresbyteriansxUlster (Northern Ireland and Ireland)xHistory, 17th century. 0aPresbyteriansxUlster (Northern Ireland and Ireland)xHistory, 18th century. 0aPresbyterianszUlster (Northern Ireland and Ireland)xHistoryy17th century. 0aPresbyterianszUlster (Northern Ireland and Ireland)xHistoryy18th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aPresbyterian community.  aProtestant community.  aRepublican.  aRobert Whan.  aScots.  aUlster.  aclergy.  adoctors.  aemigration movement.  afarmers.  aimmigration.  alawyers.  alinen trades.  amerchants.  aseparatist movement.  asocial groups.  atraders.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204189440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782041894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782041894/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles